          "iframe": null,
          "layout": "INSET_CENTER",
          "markups": [],
          "type": "IMG"
        },
        {
          "id": "c24ef87524ee_7",
          "href": null,
          "name": "5870",
          "text": "As the stream flows down the mountain what we value shapes our perceived and real needs, and in turn, our intentions and therefore the how, what and why we design. As the little stream turns into a big river, our designs express themselves in the ways we interact with each other and the relationships we form, as well as through the material objects and physical structures we create.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 89,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 38,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "EM",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            },
            {
              "end": 145,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 135,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "EM",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            },
            {
              "end": 153,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 149,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "EM",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "c24ef87524ee_8",
          "href": null,
          "name": "d9d5",
          "text": "The river of design could now be thought of as three separate but interconnected streams: social design, ecological design and economic design. As these streams feed the sea of possibilities we live our daily lives in, the structures and process we co-created or adopted (often without questioning) from previous generations, in turn, shape the way we see ourselves, our relationship to the world and what we value. Water vapour rises from the sea of possibilities and forms clouds that shed their water as they hit the mountains, feeding the springs at the source of the river of design with new ways of seeing and being.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 588,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 568,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "EM",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "c24ef87524ee_9",
          "href": null,
          "name": "c031",
          "text": "Consciousness, worldviews and intentionality manifest through design, and the designs thus created in turn shape the way we see the world, what we value, our needs, and thus our intentions.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "c24ef87524ee_10",
          "href": null,
          "name": "c863",
          "text": "Donella Meadows famously suggested that “the most effective place to intervene in a system is at the paradigm level”. If we can change the way we see the world — the explanatory maps and models we employ and the value systems we base our intentions and decision-making processes on — we are affecting change at the up-stream end of the river of design. Such subtle culture changes are fundamentally unpredictable and uncontrollable as they percolate through culture, giving rise to new and alternative structures and processes. Influencing the river of design up-stream is design at the worldview and value system level.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 353,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 332,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "EM",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            },
            {
              "end": 560,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 540,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "EM",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "c24ef87524ee_11",
          "href": null,
          "name": "09a1",
          "text": "Education, in general, and specifically the curriculum and courses created by Gaia Education, are powerful and effective examples of design at the worldview level (up-stream).",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "c24ef87524ee_12",
          "href": null,
          "name": "8f44",
          "text": "Daniel Wahl teaching on the Ecovillage Design Education course at Son Rullan (Mallorca) in 2011",
          "metadata": {
            "id": "1*wsvDJFhtBzVGWRc6jxjFpw.tiff",
            "alt": null
          },
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": "OUTSET_LEFT",
          "markups": [],
          "type": "IMG"
        },
        {
          "id": "c24ef87524ee_13",
          "href": null,
          "name": "b5fb",
          "text": "Both the EDE and the GEDS programs empower people to question and re-examine their own worldview and value systems. People are enabled to become more conscious co-designers and co-creators of the world we all share in via the way we shape our participation and design our social, ecological and economic decisions. Buckminster Fuller put it well: “You never change things by fighting the existing reality. To change something, build a new model that makes the old model obsolete.” Design is the way by which we are co-creating this new model.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
